page.title: 11TOURISM CLAPHAM CONTINUED
page.content: but some are specimen trees.We saw Holly Oak,Ashes,Mock Orange,and Yews.There are also a lot of Beeches.We saw some Rhododendrons and some were in flower.We could hear lots of birds and the sound of the beck.Much of the trail runs along a lake edge.As we walked by this lake we could see little except the sombre reflection of trees and sky.Past the lake is a "Grotto"where Reginald Farrer rested when going to the cave,just round the corner there are pine trees and more light can get in. Further on you can see the cave,there is a stream running through the cave, but that is another story. Up past the cave about 0.125 mile there is a small derelict cave called "Dead mans cave".Just round the corner is"Trow Gill".You can either return the same way or go down Clapdale Lane.
